struct name vs alias

Example:
typedef struct buffer {
   char *content;
   struct buffer *next;
} list;

"buffer" is the name of the struct.
"list" is the alias of the struct.

if you give struct an alias, you declare variables as-
list	*something;

if you didn't give struct an alias, you must declare variables as-
struct buffer *something;

struct must have a name, example "buffer", 
but it does not have to have an alias, like "list"
